<node id="&quot;BEES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Bees are insects known for their honey production and pollination activities, often found in hives and reacting to certain odors and colors."&lt;SEP&gt;"Bees are responsible for carrying pollen pellets that could be mistaken for wax.")&lt;SEP&gt;"Bees are social insects that engage in foraging and produce honey, influenced by environmental conditions."&lt;SEP&gt;"Bees are social insects that form colonies and require specific conditions for survival and thriving."&lt;SEP&gt;"Bees are social insects that live in hives and are managed by Beekeepers. They are highly sensitive to environmental conditions and the actions of Beekeepers."&lt;SEP&gt;"Bees are the insects managed in hives for honey production, whose behavior and management were central to early beekeeping practices."&lt;SEP&gt;"Bees are the insects that live in the hive and perform various tasks such as pollination and honey production."&lt;SEP&gt;"Bees are the members of a bee colony that work together to maintain the colony."&lt;SEP&gt;"Bees are the members of the hive, navigating through various environmental factors including snow and traffic."&lt;SEP&gt;"Bees are the primary inhabitants of the hives, essential for pollination and honey production."&lt;SEP&gt;"Bees are the subject of the text and their behavior is described."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d9035a4bda16d104e93b5702864022a5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a3359e9ea7553a8920a2aaf90b589a9d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9c3204e91cca2a19fc99c297c42ffa77&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e12a53f3b6ece3d5992379cab9e9f17b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-573b4d1e9d950dca730f99b82578a0ac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-482ab0ee02ac4c700ad51b839cf7790b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0b574feb85a5c2c80686afdf892d9573&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e3273db468e99ebc0efe06440d174a65&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e537830582229543208b23bd5f379d24&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e52c63f43f0f8ca942825a1048d86e1e</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SWARMS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Swarms are groups of bees that leave their original colony to find a new home."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HOLLOW TREE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"LOCATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hollow Tree is a natural habitat preferred by bees, characterized by a hollow space within a tree trunk."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;VISIBILITY AND ACCESSIBILITY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Visibility and Accessibility refer to the ease with which a hive can be seen and accessed by both the beekeeper and neighbors."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SUNLIGHT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Sunlight is a factor that affects the bees' preference for a location, providing warmth and light."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ENTRANCE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Entrance is the point of access for bees to enter and exit the hive, which should be visible and appropriately lit."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;NEIGHBORS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Neighbors are individuals or groups living in proximity to the proposed hive location."&lt;SEP&gt;"Neighbors are people living close to the beekeeper, whose apprehensions can affect the beekeeper’s actions and the visibility of the hives."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-266ae9d398bf7940b640589e500926ee&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SWARM&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A Swarm is a group of bees that leaves its original colony to find a new home."&lt;SEP&gt;"Swarm is a highly undesirable occurrence where a colony splits, losing half its population and a laying queen, affecting honey production and colony strength."&lt;SEP&gt;"Swarm is a mass movement of bees from one hive to another, often occurring in the spring or when the colony becomes too large."&lt;SEP&gt;"Swarm is a natural behavior of honeybees where a large group of bees leaves the hive to find a new home."&lt;SEP&gt;"Swarm is a significant event in the lifecycle of a bee colony where a large number of bees leave the parent colony to form a new one."&lt;SEP&gt;"Swarm is the process by which a group of bees leaves the colony to find a new home."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7251f3651e5cd421ae992f26de8129b2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7744ce257d4323a8eb4027b5dc0cb920&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e52c63f43f0f8ca942825a1048d86e1e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-54cbc98c2355f1563efcd1e13da95f19&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-41c3aaf395c33844b42f907bc25d40ac</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A Hive is a structure where bees live and produce honey, consisting of multiple frames and a body."&lt;SEP&gt;"A Hive is the dwelling place of a bee colony, typically constructed by the bees themselves or provided by humans."&lt;SEP&gt;"Hive is a structure where bees live and produce honey, central to the beekeeping practices."&lt;SEP&gt;"Hive is a structured community of bees where specific roles and processes are followed for survival and reproduction."&lt;SEP&gt;"Hive is the home of bees, where they live, produce honey, and perform other activities."&lt;SEP&gt;"Hive is the living space and structure built by the bees where they live, store food, and raise their young."&lt;SEP&gt;"Hive is the location where eggs are laid and sperm is spread over them.")&lt;SEP&gt;"Hive is the place where bees live and work."&lt;SEP&gt;"Hive is the structure where bees live and produce honey, managed by a beekeeper."&lt;SEP&gt;"Hive is the structure where bees live and produce honey, managed by the beekeeper."&lt;SEP&gt;"Hive is the structure where bees live and store honey."&lt;SEP&gt;"Hive is the structure where bees live and store their honey, and it is the center of their activity."&lt;SEP&gt;"Hive refers to a group of bees living together, facing various environmental challenges such as snow and traffic."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a3359e9ea7553a8920a2aaf90b589a9d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-53bded4e4e03e96ec81a62d617d36cdd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-573b4d1e9d950dca730f99b82578a0ac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-482ab0ee02ac4c700ad51b839cf7790b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0b574feb85a5c2c80686afdf892d9573&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d8206d1a6432719f1f3ae2c3737308ac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e3273db468e99ebc0efe06440d174a65&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e537830582229543208b23bd5f379d24&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7744ce257d4323a8eb4027b5dc0cb920&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7251f3651e5cd421ae992f26de8129b2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-41c3aaf395c33844b42f907bc25d40ac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-54cbc98c2355f1563efcd1e13da95f19</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SUNLIGHT EXPOSURE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Sunlight Exposure refers to the amount of sunlight a location receives, which is important for bee health and activity."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;TREE TRUNK&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"LOCATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Tree Trunk is part of a tree where bees may naturally form their hives, especially in hollow spaces."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE LOCATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"LOCATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hive Location is the specific site chosen for placing a bee hive, considering various factors like visibility and accessibility."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;NEIGHBOR'S APPREHENSION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Neighbor's Apprehension refers to concerns or worries expressed by neighbors about the placement of a bee hive."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;COMMON SENSE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Common Sense is the practical wisdom and sound judgment used in decision-making, especially regarding the placement of a bee hive."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BEEKEEPER&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A Beekeeper is a person who tends to beehives and practices beekeeping."&lt;SEP&gt;"A Beekeeper is an individual who manages beehives and practices beekeeping, often using protective gear."&lt;SEP&gt;"A Beekeeper is an individual who manages honeybees, often wearing protective gear but sometimes choosing to dress casually."&lt;SEP&gt;"A Beekeeper is someone responsible for managing and maintaining a bee hive."&lt;SEP&gt;"Beekeeper is a person who manages and cares for bee colonies, focusing on swarm control and prevention."&lt;SEP&gt;"Beekeeper is a person who manages and cares for honeybee colonies, often making decisions about the management and treatment of the bees."&lt;SEP&gt;"Beekeeper is a person who manages colonies and understands the challenges and processes of swarming and swarm control."&lt;SEP&gt;"beekeeper is the individual responsible for managing and maintaining the beehive, utilizing tools and stands for care."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0888a4c0f0cc346c6d0753813ecc9e49&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-53bded4e4e03e96ec81a62d617d36cdd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0b574feb85a5c2c80686afdf892d9573&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d8206d1a6432719f1f3ae2c3737308ac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e3273db468e99ebc0efe06440d174a65&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7744ce257d4323a8eb4027b5dc0cb920&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-41c3aaf395c33844b42f907bc25d40ac</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HONEY PRODUCTION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Honey Production is the process by which bees produce honey, which is a valuable product for beekeepers."&lt;SEP&gt;"Honey production is an activity performed by bees, often associated with their hives."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a3359e9ea7553a8920a2aaf90b589a9d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;POLLINATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ACTIVITY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Pollination is an activity performed by bees that helps plants reproduce and spread."&lt;SEP&gt;"Pollination is the process by which bees transfer pollen from one flower to another, aiding in plant reproduction."&lt;SEP&gt;"Pollination is the process by which pollen is transferred from the male part of a flower to the female part, enabling plant reproduction and the production of fruits and seeds."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d84a5beb18cbfd1e9fa66937ebb5293b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a3359e9ea7553a8920a2aaf90b589a9d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ELEVATED LOCATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"LOCATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Elevated Location is a position above the ground, preferred by bees for their hives."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SOUTHERLY EXPOSURE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Southerly Exposure refers to a location facing south, which provides more sunlight and warmth."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE MANAGEMENT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hive Management involves the care and maintenance of a bee hive, ensuring the health and productivity of the colony."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE SAFETY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hive Safety refers to measures taken to ensure the safety of the hive and its inhabitants."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE HEALTH&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hive Health refers to the overall well-being of the bee colony within the hive."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE MAINTENANCE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hive Maintenance involves regular checks and upkeep of the hive to prevent issues and promote health."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE INSPECTION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hive Inspection is the act of checking the hive for signs of health, pests, or other issues."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE MONITORING&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hive Monitoring involves ongoing observation of the hive to ensure its health and productivity."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE EXPANSION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hive Expansion is the process by which a hive grows larger, often requiring additional space or resources."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE DECLINE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hive Decline is the process by which a hive becomes smaller or less productive, often due to various factors."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE ABANDONMENT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hive Abandonment is the situation where a hive is left unoccupied by the bees."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE RELOCATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hive Relocation is the process of moving a hive to a new location."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE PROTECTION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hive Protection involves actions taken to safeguard the hive from threats like predators or environmental hazards."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE SECURITY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hive Security refers to measures taken to protect the hive from unauthorized access or interference."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE STABILITY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hive Stability refers to the overall stability and security of the hive structure."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE VENTILATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hive Ventilation involves ensuring proper airflow within the hive to maintain a healthy environment."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE INSULATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hive Insulation involves providing adequate insulation to maintain a stable temperature within the hive."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE LIGHTING&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hive Lighting involves providing appropriate lighting conditions within the hive."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE TEMPERATURE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hive Temperature refers to the internal temperature of the hive, which is crucial for bee health."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE HUMIDITY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hive Humidity refers to the level of moisture within the hive, which can affect bee health and productivity."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-fe239287d5735b89f51e1b54e606f90b</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hives refer to bee colonies that are protected and managed by beekeepers, often subject to vandalism and theft."&lt;SEP&gt;"Hives refer to beekeeping structures where bees live and are managed by beekeepers."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-266ae9d398bf7940b640589e500926ee&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d9035a4bda16d104e93b5702864022a5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BEEKEEPERS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Beekeepers are individuals responsible for managing and protecting the hives and bees."&lt;SEP&gt;"Beekeepers are individuals who manage and care for hives, especially beginners who need regular visits to their hives."&lt;SEP&gt;"Beekeepers are individuals who manage honey bees and often attribute higher levels of intelligence to them, which is not accurate."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-eabc0181d0cf67701c935fe928f272cb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-266ae9d398bf7940b640589e500926ee&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d9035a4bda16d104e93b5702864022a5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;REMOTE SITE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A remote site is a location far from the beekeeper's home, posing challenges for regular visits and equipment management."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-266ae9d398bf7940b640589e500926ee</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HOME&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Home is the location where the hives are ideally placed for easy access and regular visits by the beekeeper."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-266ae9d398bf7940b640589e500926ee</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;VANDALS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Vandals are groups or individuals who damage or destroy property, targeting hives in this context."&lt;SEP&gt;"Vandals are individuals who intentionally damage or destroy hives, posing a threat especially if the hives are located remotely or in the backyard."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-266ae9d398bf7940b640589e500926ee&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d9035a4bda16d104e93b5702864022a5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;THIEVES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Thieves are individuals or groups who steal property, targeting hives in this context."&lt;SEP&gt;"Thieves are individuals who steal hives, presenting a risk particularly if the hives are located in a remote area."&lt;SEP&gt;"Thieves are individuals who steal hives, presenting a risk particularly if the hives are located in remote areas."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-266ae9d398bf7940b640589e500926ee&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d9035a4bda16d104e93b5702864022a5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;VISITS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Visits refer to the regular check-ups and observations of the hives by the beekeepers."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-266ae9d398bf7940b640589e500926ee</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;EQUIPMENT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"TECHNOLOGY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Equipment includes tools such as smokers and hive tools used by beekeepers for managing hives."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-266ae9d398bf7940b640589e500926ee</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CASUAL VISITS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Casual visits are quick looks at the hives that do not involve opening them, but are still important for monitoring."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-266ae9d398bf7940b640589e500926ee</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;STUDY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A study is mentioned as a potential research topic, though none is known to have been done on the visibility and accessibility of hives."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-266ae9d398bf7940b640589e500926ee</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;OCCASIONALLY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Occasionally refers to the irregular nature of some events, such as hives being pelted with rocks or disappearing."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-266ae9d398bf7940b640589e500926ee</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;GUNSHOT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Gunshot is a form of vandalism where hives are targeted with gunfire, causing damage to the bees and frames."&lt;SEP&gt;"Gunshot is mentioned as a form of vandalism that can occur to hives, especially in remote locations."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-266ae9d398bf7940b640589e500926ee&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d9035a4bda16d104e93b5702864022a5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SHRUBBERY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Shrubbery is a type of vegetation used to mask the presence of hives, providing a natural barrier."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d9035a4bda16d104e93b5702864022a5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FENCE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A fence is a structure used to mask the presence of hives, providing a physical barrier."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d9035a4bda16d104e93b5702864022a5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BUILDING&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A building is a structure used to mask the presence of hives, providing a physical barrier."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d9035a4bda16d104e93b5702864022a5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;WINDBREAK&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A windbreak is a structure or planting designed to protect hives from excessive wind, often consisting of fences, hay bales, or shrubs."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d9035a4bda16d104e93b5702864022a5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;WINTER WINDS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Winter Winds are strong winds that can affect hives during the winter season, requiring protective measures."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d9035a4bda16d104e93b5702864022a5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SNOW&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Snow is a weather condition that can cover hives, providing some protection but also posing risks if it completely covers the hive."&lt;SEP&gt;"Snow is mentioned as a factor affecting the hive, providing some protection but also posing risks if it covers the hive completely."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-482ab0ee02ac4c700ad51b839cf7790b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d9035a4bda16d104e93b5702864022a5</data>
