  <data key="d4">3.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The relationship between Classical Soprano and Classical Alto is less pronounced compared to other vocal types, often based on registers rather than classical vocal type descriptors."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-8833a7acc64a9fb2043be36c0f159ca1</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;CLASSICAL ALTO&quot;" target="&quot;CLASSICAL MEZZO-SOPRANO&quot;">
  <data key="d4">5.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Classical Mezzo-Soprano and Classical Alto share similar vocal ranges, often overlapping in repertoire requirements."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-8833a7acc64a9fb2043be36c0f159ca1</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;HEAD REGISTER&quot;" target="&quot;LOW-VOICED SINGER&quot;">
  <data key="d4">5.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Low-Voiced Singers may need to use Head Register to achieve the higher notes required in their repertoire."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-8833a7acc64a9fb2043be36c0f159ca1</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;HEAD REGISTER&quot;" target="&quot;HIGH-VOICED SINGER&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"High-Voiced Singers primarily use Head Register for their repertoire, requiring a lighter, brighter sound."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-8833a7acc64a9fb2043be36c0f159ca1</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;CHEST REGISTER&quot;" target="&quot;LIGHT, HIGH VOICE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">6.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"A Light, High Voice often relies on Chest Register for its fullness and warmth, even when singing in the alto range."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-8833a7acc64a9fb2043be36c0f159ca1</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;REPERTOIRE&quot;" target="&quot;MIX/BELT SINGING&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Singers need to perform repertoire that requires the use of mix/belt singing techniques."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-38fe20529f06a57ccfeaaae9d98d311a</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
