  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Flight is essential for bees' Survival."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-eabc0181d0cf67701c935fe928f272cb</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;DETECTION&quot;" target="&quot;SURVIVAL&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Detection of stimuli is crucial for bees' Survival."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-eabc0181d0cf67701c935fe928f272cb</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;INCLINATION TO STING&quot;" target="&quot;ABILITY TO STING&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The Inclination to Sting develops into the Ability to Sting over time."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-eabc0181d0cf67701c935fe928f272cb</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;INCLINATION TO STING&quot;" target="&quot;MATURATION&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Maturation of the bee's Venom Glands is a key factor in the Development of the Inclination to Sting."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-eabc0181d0cf67701c935fe928f272cb</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PHYSIOLOGICAL DEVELOPMENT&quot;" target="&quot;BEHAVIORS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Physiological Development affects various Behaviors and Abilities in bees."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-eabc0181d0cf67701c935fe928f272cb</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;VOCAL FOLDS&quot;" target="&quot;ARYTENOIDS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">18.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The Arytenoids, along with the Thyroid Cartilage, form the Vocal Folds, which are essential for sound production through vibration."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-7ecb7e98904dcdb0df7a95baf5e657fc</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;VOCAL FOLDS&quot;" target="&quot;GLOTTIS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">24.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The Glottis is the opening between the Vocal Folds, which can be controlled by muscles to regulate the passage of air and produce sound."&lt;SEP&gt;"The glottis is formed by the vocal folds, which are the primary structures for sound production."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-1b275cbb65dda44f47ce44df6a2fb9cd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7ecb7e98904dcdb0df7a95baf5e657fc</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;VOCAL FOLDS&quot;" target="&quot;MUSCLES&quot;">
  <data key="d4">18.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Muscles control the length and tension of the Vocal Folds, allowing for pitch control and sound production."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-7ecb7e98904dcdb0df7a95baf5e657fc</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;VOCAL FOLDS&quot;" target="&quot;VOCAL TRACT&quot;">
  <data key="d4">18.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The Vocal Folds vibrate within the Vocal Tract, producing sound that is then amplified and modified by the shape of the vocal tract."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-7ecb7e98904dcdb0df7a95baf5e657fc</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;VOCAL FOLDS&quot;" target="&quot;LARYNX&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx houses the vocal folds, which are responsible for producing sound."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;VOCAL FOLDS&quot;" target="&quot;THORAX&quot;">
  <data key="d4">5.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The thorax indirectly affects the vocal folds through the muscles that exert forces for respiration."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;VOCAL FOLDS&quot;" target="&quot;ABDUCTION&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"During abduction, the vocal folds open in the shape of the letter V during normal breathing."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-1b275cbb65dda44f47ce44df6a2fb9cd</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;VOCAL FOLDS&quot;" target="&quot;ADDUCTION&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"During adduction, the vocal folds close to produce sound during phonation."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-1b275cbb65dda44f47ce44df6a2fb9cd</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;VOCAL FOLDS&quot;" target="&quot;LAMINA PROPRIA&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The lamina propria provides support and flexibility to the vocal folds."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-1b275cbb65dda44f47ce44df6a2fb9cd</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;VOCAL FOLDS&quot;" target="&quot;EPITHELIAL LAYER&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The epithelial layer surrounds the vocal folds and is kept moist with mucus."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-1b275cbb65dda44f47ce44df6a2fb9cd</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;VOCAL FOLDS&quot;" target="&quot;CORE MUSCLE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The core muscle is part of the vocal folds and provides the necessary movement for sound production."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-1b275cbb65dda44f47ce44df6a2fb9cd</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;VOCAL FOLDS&quot;" target="&quot;WAVELIKE MOTION&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The wavelike motion of the outer layer of the vocal folds is essential for sound production."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-1b275cbb65dda44f47ce44df6a2fb9cd</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;VOCAL FOLDS&quot;" target="&quot;THIGH MUSCLES&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Thigh muscles are used as an analogy to describe the adduction and abduction movements of the vocal folds."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-1b275cbb65dda44f47ce44df6a2fb9cd</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;VOCAL FOLDS&quot;" target="&quot;CHEST MUSCLES&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Chest muscles are also used as an analogy to describe the adduction and abduction movements of the vocal folds."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-1b275cbb65dda44f47ce44df6a2fb9cd</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;VOCAL FOLDS&quot;" target="&quot;ALVEOLI&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Air stored in the Alveoli is used to set the Vocal Folds into vibration for speech and sound production."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-3fb90ae6bf97fbc21cb066ced098ee6c</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;THYROID CARTILAGE&quot;" target="&quot;THYROARYTENOID MUSCLE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The Thyroarytenoid Muscle originates from the Thyroid Cartilage, connecting it to the Arytenoids and controlling the shortening of the Vocal Folds."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-7ecb7e98904dcdb0df7a95baf5e657fc</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;THYROID CARTILAGE&quot;" target="&quot;CRICOTHYROID MUSCLE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The Cricothyroid Muscle connects the Thyroid Cartilage to the Cricoid Cartilage, controlling the elongation of the Vocal Folds through its action."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-7ecb7e98904dcdb0df7a95baf5e657fc</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;THYROID CARTILAGE&quot;" target="&quot;CRICOID CARTILAGE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">14.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The Thyroid Cartilage connects with the Cricoid Cartilage via muscles, forming part of the larynx structure."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-7ecb7e98904dcdb0df7a95baf5e657fc</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;ARYTENOIDS&quot;" target="&quot;MUSCLES&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Muscles connect between the Arytenoids and other cartilages, controlling the movement of the vocal folds."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-7ecb7e98904dcdb0df7a95baf5e657fc</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNGITIS&quot;" target="&quot;APHONIA&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Laryngitis can lead to Aphonia, a condition where the vocal folds are tightly coupled, making phonation difficult or impossible."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c680a6b8b3e81c2296be9f38f10110eb</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;EPIGLOTTIS&quot;" target="&quot;GLOTTIS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">14.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The Epiglottis, located above the Glottis, prevents food and liquid from entering the lungs during swallowing, protecting the respiratory system."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-7ecb7e98904dcdb0df7a95baf5e657fc</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;EPIGLOTTIS&quot;" target="&quot;MUSCLES&quot;">
  <data key="d4">14.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Muscles control the movement of the Epiglottis, preventing food and liquid from entering the lungs during swallowing."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-7ecb7e98904dcdb0df7a95baf5e657fc</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;GLOTTIS&quot;" target="&quot;MUSCLES&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Muscles control the opening and closing of the Glottis, regulating the passage of air."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-7ecb7e98904dcdb0df7a95baf5e657fc</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;GLOTTIS&quot;" target="&quot;LARYNX&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Sound is produced in the glottis, a space within the larynx formed by the vocal folds."&lt;&lt;SEP&gt;"The glottis is part of the larynx, located in the throat, where sound is produced."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-6e594c09c6de0c01da248106da72ab77&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;GLOTTIS&quot;" target="&quot;THORAX&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The glottis, a part of the larynx, is located within the thorax and is influenced by respiration."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;GLOTTIS&quot;" target="&quot;WOMEN&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"In women, the glottis is about the size of a dime."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-1b275cbb65dda44f47ce44df6a2fb9cd</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;GLOTTIS&quot;" target="&quot;MEN&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"In men, the glottis can approach the diameter of a quarter."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-1b275cbb65dda44f47ce44df6a2fb9cd</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;VOCAL FUNCTION&quot;" target="&quot;SOUND PRODUCTION&quot;">
  <data key="d4">18.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Sound Production is a component of Vocal Function, which includes the ability to produce and control sound."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-7ecb7e98904dcdb0df7a95baf5e657fc</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;RESONANCE&quot;" target="&quot;VOCAL TRACT&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Resonance occurs within the Vocal Tract, enhancing the quality and timbre of the voice."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-7ecb7e98904dcdb0df7a95baf5e657fc</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;THORAX&quot;">
  <data key="d4">6.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The thorax contains the larynx, which is involved in both respiration and vocalization."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;RESPIRATION&quot;">
  <data key="d4">17.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx is involved in respiration by producing sounds and vibrations."&lt;&lt;SEP&gt;"The larynx plays a role in respiration by serving as a sphincter valve and assisting in lifting and childbirth."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;SPEECH&quot;">
  <data key="d4">20.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx is essential for producing speech by vibrating the vocal folds."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;VOICE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">10.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx is the primary organ for voice production, involving the vocal folds and glottis."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;ADAM'S APPLE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx is sometimes referred to as the Adam's apple, a visible prominence in the neck."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;FOREIGN OBJECTS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx acts as a sphincter valve to prevent foreign objects from entering the lungs."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;ABDOMINAL PRESSURE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">14.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx can be used to increase abdominal pressure for activities like lifting and childbirth."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;INHALATION POSTURE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">6.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Maintaining a degree of inhalation posture during exhalation is recommended for better breathing."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;EXHALATION&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx is involved in exhalation by vibrating the vocal folds to produce sound."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;INHALATION&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx is involved in inhalation by facilitating the intake of air."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;MUSCULAR ANTAGONISM&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Practicing muscular antagonism, maintaining an inhalation posture during exhalation, is recommended for better breathing."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;RESPIRATORY FUNCTIONS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx has secondary respiratory functions, including exhalation and inhalation."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;COMMUNICATION&quot;">
  <data key="d4">10.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx is essential for communication through speech and singing."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;SPHINCTER VALVE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx acts as a sphincter valve to protect the airway."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;DEFECATION&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx can be used to increase abdominal pressure for defecation."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;CHILDBIRTH&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx can be used to increase abdominal pressure for childbirth."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;BREATH&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx is involved in breath production through the vibration of vocal folds."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;AIRWAY&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx is involved in protecting the airway through its sphincter valve function."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;RESPIRATORY SYSTEM&quot;">
  <data key="d4">10.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx is a part of the respiratory system, involved in respiration and vocalization."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;VOICE BOX&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx is also known as the voice box, a complex structure involved in speech and singing."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;RESPIRATORY MUSCLES&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx works in conjunction with respiratory muscles for respiration and vocalization."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;RESPIRATORY FUNCTION&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx has respiratory functions, including exhalation and inhalation."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;VOICE PRODUCTION&quot;">
  <data key="d4">10.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx is the primary organ for voice production, involving the vocal folds and glottis."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;RESPIRATORY VALVE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx acts as a respiratory valve to protect the airway."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;RESPIRATORY PROTECTION&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx provides protection for the airway through its sphincter valve function."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;RESPIRATORY SUPPORT&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx supports respiration through its involvement in vocalization and breathing."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dca9303a607f377e06cf6c0a4f271e11</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;LARYNX&quot;" target="&quot;RESPIRATORY FUNCTIONING&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The larynx is involved in respiratory functioning, including exhalation and inhalation."&lt;</data>
